<div class="framework-grid">
  <article><span>Buffett</span><strong>Earn concentration</strong><p>Large weights require understandable, durable economics and a price that protects against error.</p></article>
  <article><span>Munger</span><strong>Invert before sizing</strong><p>Ask how the position can permanently impair capital, then keep re-evaluating the big bets.</p></article>
  <article><span>Howard Marks</span><strong>Budget downside</strong><p>Size from permanent-loss severity, cycle position, and correlation rather than upside alone.</p></article>
  <article><span>Druckenmiller</span><strong>Press and cut</strong><p>Increase when evidence and payoff improve together; reduce when the forward distribution breaks.</p></article>
  <article><span>Damodaran</span><strong>Make the story explicit</strong><p>Translate narrative into probabilities and values, then stress the fragility of those estimates.</p></article>
  <article><span>Galloway</span><strong>Preserve staying power</strong><p>Concentration can build wealth only when one miss cannot remove your ability to remain in the game.</p></article>
</div>
